aditional material to the needs of an audience versed in reading romance and other secular genres. This study scrutinises the implications of the Scottish poet's narrative strategies with respect to the Scottishness of the Legendary and its overall place in the hagiographic landscape of late medieval Britain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian hagiography in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexScottish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aReligion in literature. 0aSaints in literature. 0aScottish literaturexHistory and criticismxTo 1700. 0aScottish poetryxHistory and criticismxTo 1700. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aHagiography.  aNarrative art.  aNarrative theory.  aSaints’ lives.  aScotland.1 avon Contzen, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610026940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526100269423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526100269/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles